1 (5) A member of the air pollution control board is eligible to succeed himself or
2 herself. A vacancy in the membership shall be filled by an appointee of the mayor
3 or of the county judge/executive as the case may be, for the unexpired portion of the
4 term. An appointee to a vacancy shall have the same qualifications as any regularly
5 appointed member.
6 (6) Any member of the board appointed by a mayor may be removed, for cause, after a
7 hearing, by the legislative body of such city or consolidated local government, and
8 after ten (10) days' notice in writing shall have been given to the member, which
9 notice shall embrace the charges preferred against him or her. At the hearing he or
10 she may be represented by counsel. The finding of the legislative body shall be
11 final and removal results in vacancy in such office.
12 (7) Any member of the board appointed by a county judge/executive may be removed,
13 for cause, after a hearing, by the fiscal court of such county, and after ten (10) days'
14 notice in writing shall have been given to the member, which notice shall embrace
15 the charges preferred against him or her. At the hearing he or she may be
16 represented by counsel. The finding of the fiscal court shall be final and removal
17 results in vacancy in such office.
18 (8) As used in this section "mayor" means the chief executive of the city or
19 consolidated local government whether the official designation of his or her office
20 is mayor, city manager, or otherwise.
21 (9) Notwithstanding subsections (1) and (2) of this section, when a city of the first class
22 and a county containing such city have in effect a compact under KRS 79.310 to
23 79.330, the air pollution control board shall consist of seven (7) members, four (4)
24 of whom shall be appointed by the county judge/executive with the approval of the
25 fiscal court and three (3) of whom shall be appointed by the mayor, with the
26 approval of the legislative body, of the first-class city within such county. The
27 terms of such members shall be three (3) years, and until their successors are
